Dear Governor Purdue,

I have the privilege of being witness to your first months in office as the first woman governor of this great state of North Carolina. Your tenacity and compassion for your citizens inspires me during this time of our fiscal challenge. I have fallen victim to a bureaucratic anomaly rife with inconsistency and unfairness. Your audience and attention to this issue I am requesting and I will deeply value your input.


I entered the North Carolina Department of Education as a music teacher in Durham, North Carolina in the fall of 2004. Because my degrees are in music performance(Bachelor/ Masters) I was issued a Lateral Entry-Provisional License. I attended all of the Beginning Teacher activities as mandated by the school system and I submitted and successfully completed the observation cycle. In August of 2005, I relocated to Fairfax County where I served successfully, as a music teacher for three years.. I desired to relocate to be closer to my parents and initiated that pursuit in the spring of last year.


I contacted Department of Pupil Instruction (DPI) in May of 2008 and inquired if I would be allowed to teach. A DPI representative informed me that yes, I had two more years on my Provisional/ Lateral Entry license. During these remaining two years, I would be able to fulfill the education requirements that I lack. (As my Bachelors and Masters are in Performance) I simply needed to seek vacant positions, interview, and the interested counties would then contact DPI. I interviewed in the counties of Mecklenburg, Orange, and Guilford. I was offered a contract in Orange County and Guilford County expressed great interest in me as a candidate, but had a concern with DPI. I was told to contact DPI which I did immediately. I was surprised to discover that DPI had switched polices regarding how the 3 years of my license was interpreted. They decided that the three years of a license were to be consecutive. I was told that I would not be eligible to employment as a teacher until August of 2010 or until I was able to take the appropriate classes. This news created great fear turmoil for me, as I am a single mother of two boys, nine and twelve. Plans had been made to relocate to North Carolina based on the May conversation I had with DPI. I was forced to move in with my mother who in September was diagnosed with stage four cancers. The circumstances merited that I cash out my retirement to meet my financial demands. Finally, I became employed as a Teacher’s Assistant in Wake County. Yes, I was thankful to find work, but I realized that I would be unable to take the coursework that would allow me to teach due to the salary that I would receive. In December I was contacted by DPI with what I thought to be good news. As I was told, DPI realized that there shift in how the three years contract years of the Provisional License had created a financial hardship. I was not the only individual in this predicament. If
I could prove that I was offered a job based upon the initial interpretation of “three years” I could indeed work. I state that yes, I had been issued a job offer and that I had that contract in my possession. Unfortunately, a month later I was told that I would only be able to teach in the position for which I received an offer. I replied” ...how absurd...that the position was not open…the position was not held for me…DPI was offering a faux olive branch…” to which that I was correct…and that yes, it was unfair.

Governor Purdue, it is my hope that you can help me. I want to teach and I am outstanding at what I do. I remain anxious to take the required coursework and I look forward to how it will increase my effectiveness as a music teacher. I want to provide a better standard of living for my two sons and myself. DPI has been unfair to me and I assume that I am not the only person that has experienced this treatment. Whatever you are moved to do or choose to do, I will appreciate and will respect.

With every good wish, I remain…


Denise Forbes

