Dear Governor Perdue:

I am greatly alarmed to hear that the Appropriations Act of 2009 includes a proposal to eliminate tuition grants for graduates of the  North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics who attend UNC universities. 

My son is a senior at NCSSM due to graduate in two months.  I am upset at this proposal for the following reasons:

1.  With graduation two months away and our commitment deposit already made to NC State University, our options at this time are gone.  All scholarship and application deadlines have long since passed.  We were counting on the the State of North Carolina to keep its word to provide this tuition grant to defray expenses to attend NC State where he plans to study microbiology and later medical research.

2.  While attending NCSSM is a unique and exceptional experience, students there give up a lot to attend.  I'm sure they are all grateful for this opportunity, as are we, but had these students remained at their local schools, they would no doubtedly be in the top 5% of their classes with many scholarship offers as a result.  They gave up these opportunities as well as the opportunity to earn income for college tuition since they are not allowed to work while attending NCSSM.  They did this willingly in order to get a top notch education.  They believed that working extremely hard would have rewards, one of them being the tuition grant.

3.  NCSSM classes are much more rigorous than in other public high schools.  Students there do not have perfect 4.0 GPA's and work extremely hard to get A's and B's and sometimes even C's.  I believe that these students have gone above and beyond and and made many sacrifices.  

4.  Had we known that the tuition grant was in jeopardy, my son could have applied to other universities closer to home which might have been more affordable for us.  With two months left until graduation, we no longer have this option. 

4.  Many perceive all of the students at NCSSM as kids from wealthy families.  Nothing could be farther from the truth.  There is a great cross-section of students at the school including those from rural counties of  North Carolina and many minorities.  They all have two things in common - motivation and intelligence.  Many of these students would not have had the opportunity to get the caliber of education in their home school that they are receiving at NCSSM.  In addition, funding four years of college would be difficult without careful planning.  Leading them to believe that their college tuition would be covered and then snatching it away at this late date will be devastating.

I understand that we are all going through tough times, but surely breaking a promise to some of the brightest students in our state is not the way to go.  If you must rescind the tuition grant program, please begin with next year's junior class members who can choose to attend NCSSM fully aware that the tuition grant is no longer available.   Pulling the rug out from under this year's senior class at the 11th hour cannot possibly be what our legislators have in mind.

For these reasons, I beg  you to reconsider this proposal.  These students represent the future of our great state.

LouAnn Spencer
New Hanover County

