Dear Governor Purdue,

I am writing to you today to express my deep concern over section 9.7(a) of the Appropriation Act of 2009, which was sponsored by Senators Garrou, Albertson, Dannelly & Swindell. Section 9.7(a) deals specifically with the repeal of the Full Tuition Grant to students who graduate from the North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics.   This repeal would be effective at the end of this school year and would directly impact the current juniors and seniors at NCSSM as well as future students. 
While I am aware that you have received a communication (dated March 31, 2009) from Dr. Gerald Boarman, Chancellor of NCSSM, I felt it critical to write myself, as one of your constituents, to let you know how strongly I oppose the elimination of this tuition grant to NCSSM students and to urge you to stop this repeal and continue the tuition grant.

As you are aware, graduates of NCSSM, one of the most prestigious schools in North Carolina, and indeed the U.S. and the world, and a model for many similar schools around the world, receive a tuition grant to any campus of the North Carolina University system.  This is very important and has proven that with this tuition grant, these students, some of the best and brightest in North Carolina, remain in North Carolina for their higher education.  As I am sure you are also aware, there is a direct correlation between where a student completes his/her higher education and where he/she ultimately resides, works and pays taxes as an adult.    North Carolina needs to keep these students in North Carolina.  The success of the tuition grant program since it was established, shows that it works. The number of graduates of NCSSM who remain in-state has risen from approximately 55% to approximately 80%. 

While I recognize the current financial crisis we all face, both personally and as citizens of North Carolina, North Carolina has always been at the forefront, been a leader, in education and appropriate education initiatives.  We cannot allow this to change.  The NCSSM Tuition Grant needs to be restored.  Some of the reasons to restore this grant are as follows:

1.  Based on the promise of this academic award, most of the current senior students and their families made decisions to attend UNC institutions prior to the release this budget proposal. In many cases, they declined scholarships elsewhere. For these families, especially, it is too late to make alternate plans and avoid serious financial harm.  Without this tuition grant, which was already promised to them by the State of North Carolina, some of these students may not be able to complete their higher education as originally planned.
2. Both junior and senior families have made important educational and financial decisions based upon this compact, the tuition grant which was promised by the State of NC when they made the decision to apply to and attend NCSSM.  This has also served as an incentive for academic achievement since the students' middle school years.  This incentive extends beyond the current student body but is also well known among current middle school and high school students, thus giving them another reason to work and study hard and seek to attend NCSSM and then, once enrolled, to successfully complete their studies at NCSSM.

3.  As mentioned above, the tuition grant is symbolic of the importance placed by North Carolinians on educational excellence and needs to continue to keep North Carolina at the forefront of education for our citizens.

Please do everything possible to restore this tuition grant for NCSSM and its students. 

Thank you for your attention.  Should you have any questions or wish further information, please do not hesitate to contact me. 

