Dear Governor Perdue:

For many years, North Carolina’s esteemed early education system has been a source of pride for the state and a priceless benefit for its children and families. In fact, the More at Four program earned praise just this week by the National Institute for Early Education (NIEER) as a national model for high-quality early education.



Unfortunately, this valuable program - currently one of only two in the nation to meet all 10 quality benchmarks established by NIEER – now faces a grim possibility. The Senate's budget proposal, expected to pass today by a wide margin, could  ultimately decimate the program entirely. This would be devastating for children, for working families and for the state’s economic health in the future.



The Senate’s budget proposal threatens a cut of $40 million in state funding for More at Four and changes the purpose of the program entirely by moving the program out of the Department of Public Instruction and shifting its focus from pre-kindergarten education to welfare support.



If the Senate proposal passes, More at Four would no longer be considered a pre-k program by the National Institute for Early Education Research and North Carolina would, in effect, offer no state-funded pre-k to its families. Under this bill, children could be forced to leave the program in the middle of a school year because their eligibility would be contingent upon their parents keeping their jobs, enrolling in school, or maintaining their income below a certain level throughout the year.



Having heard you describe your support for high-quality pre-k in your State of the State address, we urge you to step in and oppose the Senate’s budget proposal, which would negatively impact nearly 30,000 children served by More at Four. Especially during this economic downturn, all families need access to high-quality pre-k, and North Carolina needs to invest in building its human capital – starting with its youngest citizens.



Your leadership on this critical issue is needed to ensure that North Carolina’s children do not lose the opportunity to attend high-quality pre-k. The nation will be watching.



Pre-K Now, a campaign of the Pew Center on the States, collaborates with advocates and policymakers to lead a movement toward high-quality, voluntary pre-kindergarten for all three and four year olds. We look forward to serving as a resource as you work to protect and improve North Carolina’s nationally renowned early education system. Please feel free to contact me or have your staff contact me at dgonzales@preknow.org or 202-862-9861 should you have any questions or wish to discuss this issue further.

